<Content>Great decor design but small room and little sleep The hotel lobby has a very interesting design and is rather psychedelic in an Austin Powers sort of way. The room was small - no cupboard to hang clothes, only a few hooks on the wall for hanging clothes and some space below the bed for storing clothes and other stuff. The bathroom walls are made of glass, not least to show off the nice mosaic tiling design and also give the room a feel that it is bigger than it really is. I stayed on my own so didnt have the problem faced by other commentators of having to lose dignity in heeding the call of Mother Nature in full view of their partners. The hotel was converted from a pre-war shophouse, so as with the nature of these buildings the sounds from the streets can echo into the room easily. After I reflected this to the staff, he promptly changed my room to one that faced the back of the street. Even so, I was still bothered by sound. The blinds also do not shield out light sufficiently in the way that I am used to, so I really had some problems getting enough sleep because of the brightness and sounds. In conclusion, you can consider this hotel if you are happy to sleep very little, love modern art designs and wish to feel exotic. 
